<HTML> 
<HEAD>
<TITLE>	Objectives, Principles, Approach: Phase II</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

<P>
<P><B>_________________________________________________________________________________</B><BR>
Document Name<B>:	</B><B>Objectives, Principles, Approach: Phase II</B><BR>
Date:	<B>		</B><B>02/01/95</B><BR>
Owner:	<B>		</B><B>National Performance Review</B>		<BR>

<B>_________________________________________________________________________________</B><BR>
****************************************************<BR>

<P>NPR Phase II Putting It Together: Objectives,<BR>

<P>Working Principles, and Approach<BR>

<P>****************************************************<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>The driving question for the first phase of NPR was<BR>

<P>&quot;how can government work better and cost less?&quot;  The <BR>

<P>overall purpose of the second phase of NPR is to<BR>

<P>answer the question, &quot;what should the federal<BR>

<P>government be doing?&quot;  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>What is our vision of success?  Our vision of<BR>

<P>success is a smaller federal government that helps<BR>

<P>communities and individuals  solve their own<BR>

<P>problems, and delivers quality services where<BR>

<P>Americans believe they are receiving value for their<BR>

<P>tax dollars and know who they can hold accountable.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>How will we know when we are successful?  We will<BR>

<P>know we are successful when there are fewer federal<BR>

<P>agencies and programs, when there are fewer<BR>

<P>decisions being made by the federal government that<BR>

<P>can best be made elsewhere, when customers of the<BR>

<P>federal government see substantial improvements in<BR>

<P>services, and when Americans increase their level of<BR>

<P>trust in the federal government.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>How will we do our work?  To do this work, we<BR>

<P>propose four concurrent efforts (agency<BR>

<P>restructuring, devolution of federal programs to<BR>

<P>states and localities, regulatory reinvention,<BR>

<P>and continued implementation of NPR phase I).  These<BR>

<P>will be supplemented a set of crosscutting teams<BR>

<P>that will help the agency and advisory teams by<BR>

<P>providing expertise on restructuring techniques,<BR>

<P>such as privatization and streamlining, that would<BR>

<P>be helpful to agencies in developing their options<BR>

<P>proposals.  Also, since most of the recommendations<BR>

<P>will require legislative action, we will communicate<BR>

<P>early with congressional offices. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>** 1. Agency Restructuring Initiative **<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>*Objectives*:  Examine the basic missions of<BR>

<P>government to find and eliminate things that don't<BR>

<P>need to be done by the federal government and sort<BR>

<P>out how best to do the things the federal government<BR>

<P>should continue to do.  Create a smaller federal<BR>

<P>government -- by eliminating, privatizing, or<BR>

<P>devolving programs and subsidies -- that focuses on<BR>

<P>areas where the federal government should provide<BR>

<P>quality service to its customers -- and can do a<BR>

<P>good job of it.  The resulting smaller government<BR>

<P>will be results-oriented and customer focused.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>*Working Principles*:  Agencies have been asked to<BR>

<P>fundamentally rethink their missions.  The Vice<BR>

<P>President (in a January 3, 1995 memo to agency<BR>

<P>heads) proposes the following criteria:<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- If your agency were eliminated, how would the<BR>

<P>   goals or programs of your agency be undertaken --<BR>

<P>   by other agencies, by states or localities, by<BR>

<P>   the private sector, or not at all?<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- If there are goals or programs of national<BR>

<P>   importance that will remain undone and require a<BR>

<P>   federal role in order to be accomplished, should<BR>

<P>   they be done differently than they are being done<BR>

<P>   today in order to enhance service to the<BR>

<P>   customers? <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- How do your customers (not just interest groups)<BR>

<P>   feel about the possible eliminations or changes?  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Attachment 1 contains the Vice President's memo<BR>

<P>which is accompanied by a sample &quot;decision tree&quot;<BR>

<P>that agencies should use to develop their analysis<BR>

<P>of their mission and programs.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>*Approach*:  The agencies themselves will create<BR>

<P>internal review teams. These agency-led teams will<BR>

<P>be headed, in most cases, by the agency's chief<BR>

<P>operating officer. In the case of smaller agencies,<BR>

<P>the agency head may choose to lead the team.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>OMB, NPR, and appropriate White House policy<BR>

<P>councils also will create a set of six small<BR>

<P>advisory teams covering the roughly 150 federal<BR>

<P>agencies. Five of these teams -- with the same<BR>

<P>jurisdictions as OMB's resource management offices<BR>

<P>-- will focus assistance on the 19 major agencies<BR>

<P>that have not yet put forward a Phase II<BR>

<P>restructuring proposal.  Smaller agencies, in most<BR>

<P>cases, will be reviewed by the sixth team, in the<BR>

<P>context of related program areas.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>To assist the agencies, several crosscutting teams<BR>

<P>will offer a series of topical workshops and<BR>

<P>seminars for agencies to share information about<BR>

<P>soliciting customer input, privatization, creating<BR>

<P>voucher programs, etc. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>The dynamics of the review process will be similar<BR>

<P>to that used by OMB, NPR, and the agencies<BR>

<P>participating in the first five restructurings<BR>

<P>announced on December 19th.   <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- The overall review will be a collaborative effort<BR>

<P>   among the President's Management Council, agency<BR>

<P>   staff, and NPR, OMB, and White House policy<BR>

<P>   staffs. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- Agencies will be asked to prepare a short 3-5<BR>

<P>   page summary paper (with any needed attachments)<BR>

<P>   proposing options for both termination and major<BR>

<P>   restructuring of their operations along the lines<BR>

<P>   of the principles articulated by the Vice<BR>

<P>   President in his letter to agency heads.  The<BR>

<P>   advisory teams will assist agencies in preparing<BR>

<P>   the option paper and encourage agencies to<BR>

<P>   present bold, innovative ideas (see Attachment 2 <BR>

<P>   for format).   <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- The draft option paper would then be used to<BR>

<P>   guide the agency's discussion before the Phase II<BR>

<P>   Steering Committee.  The option papers for large<BR>

<P>   agencies should be delivered to OMB for<BR>

<P>   distribution to the Phase II Steering Committee<BR>

<P>   at least 48 hours in advance of the meeting.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- We currently envision two agency presentations<BR>

<P>   that will center around the option papers for the<BR>

<P>   large agencies: one to the Phase II Steering<BR>

<P>   Committee and the second, after any revisions to<BR>

<P>   the option paper, to the Vice President and the<BR>

<P>   Director of OMB to take to the President for<BR>

<P>   final decisions.  Presidential decisions would be<BR>

<P>   made public as soon as practical and work should<BR>

<P>   begin immediately on draft legislation. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- For small agencies, the draft option paper will<BR>

<P>   go to NPR and initial decisions on groups of<BR>

<P>   small agencies will be made by the Phase II<BR>

<P>   Steering Committee.  If the initial  <BR>

<P>   recommendation is to terminate or dramatically<BR>

<P>   restructure a small agency, a second meeting will<BR>

<P>   be held where the agency head will have an<BR>

<P>   opportunity to make a presentation.  A second<BR>

<P>   presentation may then be scheduled with the Vice<BR>

<P>   President and Director of OMB before asking the<BR>

<P>   President for a final decision.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- The general timetable for the completion of the<BR>

<P>   first presentation of options is anticipated to<BR>

<P>   be between mid-February and mid-March 1995. The<BR>

<P>   second will begin shortly after the first<BR>

<P>   presentations.  A draft timetable for these<BR>

<P>   papers and presentations is available as a<BR>

<P>   separate handout.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>The final product, in most cases, will be draft<BR>

<P>legislation; an extensive report is not envisioned<BR>

<P>at this time.  In addition to drafting legislation,<BR>

<P>agencies then will be tasked to develop strategies<BR>

<P>for operating their restructured missions.  Agencies<BR>

<P>will be asked to prepare this information, in<BR>

<P>conjunction with their strategies for how they will<BR>

<P>collect performance information and shift to<BR>

<P>output/outcome measures of performance.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>NPR's crosscutting teams will conduct a series of<BR>

<P>topical workshops on these and related issues<BR>

<P>(see also item 5).<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>** 2.Federalism Initiative **<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>*Objective*:  Where states and localities can<BR>

<P>perform functions more effectively than the federal<BR>

<P>government, the federal government should devolve as<BR>

<P>much authority as possible to states, localities,<BR>

<P>and individuals for the operation of programs.  They<BR>

<P>will be judged on the quality of their services and<BR>

<P>whether programs achieve agreed upon results. In<BR>

<P>cases where a direct federal role remains, the<BR>

<P>federal government's participation will be in a<BR>

<P>partnership role.  Federal agencies would move to a<BR>

<P>&quot;steer, don't row&quot; role, focus on developing the<BR>

<P>baseline data for assessing performance, creating<BR>

<P>incentives for higher performance, and conducting<BR>

<P>reviews to assure national goals are being met.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>* Working Principles and Options: *    <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>The Constitution gives the Federal Government a<BR>

<P>preeminent role in clearly defined categories of<BR>

<P>activity.  In addition, key historical events have<BR>

<P>led the Federal Government to assume certain core<BR>

<P>functions.  The constitutional and historical list<BR>

<P>includes, at a minimum, the following:  conducting<BR>

<P>national defense and foreign relations; safeguarding<BR>

<P>individual rights, as defined by the Constitution;<BR>

<P>regulating interstate commerce; stabilizing the<BR>

<P>national economy; and making basic social insurance<BR>

<P>widely available.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>There are other areas where the Federal role is not<BR>

<P>defined as clearly, yet where it may nevertheless be<BR>

<P>quite important.  The nature of certain public<BR>

<P>interests may lead them to be best achieved with<BR>

<P>Federal leadership or participation.  These<BR>

<P>interests include addressing:<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>~ activities having spillover effects that cross<BR>

<P>  State lines (e.g., some environmental issues or<BR>

<P>  investments in transportation networks); and<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>~ distributional challenges caused by mobility of<BR>

<P>  low and high income households and businesses, in<BR>

<P>  which competition among jurisdictions can reduce<BR>

<P>  the effectiveness of tax and transfer systems.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Importantly, however, States, localities,<BR>

<P>businesses, nonprofit institutions, and individuals<BR>

<P>may each have comparative advantages in addressing<BR>

<P>much -- or even all -- of many of these<BR>

<P>responsibilities.  In particular, the fact that a<BR>

<P>problem is widespread does not necessarily mean that<BR>

<P>the Federal Government is best suited to tackling<BR>

<P>it.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>The Federal Government uses several major tools to<BR>

<P>affect outcomes that are ultimately at the State,<BR>

<P>local, or even individual level.  These include:<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>~ requirements -- Federal laws and regulations can<BR>

<P>  require or forbid various processes or outcomes;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>~ financing -- Federal grants, credit assistance,<BR>

<P>  transfer payments, and tax policies can assist<BR>

<P>  State and local governments, businesses, or<BR>

<P>  individuals;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>~ direct service delivery --  Federal employees can<BR>

<P>  directly provide a service; and<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>~ information provision -- the Federal Government<BR>

<P>  can collect information and promote its exchange.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>For each of these methods, Federal involvement can<BR>

<P>range from zero to significant. In addition, mixes<BR>

<P>of methods are possible; thus, the Federal role in a<BR>

<P>given area (such as pollution control or education<BR>

<P>for disadvantaged students) might involve, for<BR>

<P>example, minimal service delivery, partial funding,<BR>

<P>and significant requirements.  Moreover, such<BR>

<P>mixed Federal roles can range from uncoordinated<BR>

<P>collections of programs to carefully designed shared<BR>

<P>responsibilities.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>In developing options for an improved Federal role,<BR>

<P>therefore, teams should seek to ensure that the<BR>

<P>Federal Government is undertaking a well justified<BR>

<P>mix of activities and that the nature of Federal<BR>

<P>involvement corresponds well to the type of problem<BR>

<P>being addressed.  There are a number of ways to<BR>

<P>realign Federal and non-Federal responsibilities to<BR>

<P>increase program effectiveness.  For example:<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>~ A reinvention strategy could focus on moving to a<BR>

<P>  reduced Federal role along one dimension (e.g., a<BR>

<P>  restrictive regulation could be relaxed).  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>~ Alternatively, a combination of strategies within<BR>

<P>  one area might be used.  For instance, development<BR>

<P>  of more flexible requirements might enable Federal<BR>

<P>  financing to be reduced.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>~ Yet another approach could be a swap across<BR>

<P>  different activities.  For example, the<BR>

<P>  Federal Government could take increased<BR>

<P>  responsibility for financing or directly <BR>

<P>  providing one set of activities (it might fund<BR>

<P>  medical programs or administer certain tax <BR>

<P>  programs) in exchange for greater State and local<BR>

<P>  responsibilities in other areas (such as funding<BR>

<P>  welfare or education programs).<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>One approach, which is a combined strategy, is the<BR>

<P>use of performance partnerships.  This approach is<BR>

<P>proposed for several major areas in the President's<BR>

<P>FY 1996 Budget Approach:  Ideally, any federalism<BR>

<P>proposals will be encompassed by an agency's overall<BR>

<P>restructuring effort, as devolution and new forms of<BR>

<P>intergovernmental partnership are among the options<BR>

<P>to be considered by all agencies in how to improve<BR>

<P>services to customers.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>The agencies will take the lead in developing<BR>

<P>intergovernmental proposals.  A team of internal<BR>

<P>advisors will be created from NPR, the White House<BR>

<P>(Domestic Policy Council, National Economic Council,<BR>

<P>Intergovernmental Affairs, Council of Economic<BR>

<P>Advisors), OMB, and Treasury to support the<BR>

<P>agency-based team efforts.  This advisory team will<BR>

<P>provide technical assistance (conceptual framework,<BR>

<P>options, background papers, list of experts,<BR>

<P>bibliography); help involve customers/stakeholders<BR>

<P>by soliciting ideas and vetting ideas (advisory<BR>

<P>panel, focus groups, workshops, etc); share<BR>

<P>proposals across agencies; look for cross-agency<BR>

<P>opportunities; and assist with crafting financing<BR>

<P>options.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Some initial intergovernmental performance<BR>

<P>partnership proposals have been proposed as part<BR>

<P>of the President's FY 1996 budget. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>** 3.  Regulatory Reinvention Initiative **<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>*Objectives*:  Reassess how regulations are<BR>

<P>developed, whether we should delete or change<BR>

<P>existing regulations, and how the federal government<BR>

<P>enforces its regulations.  In all cases, we are<BR>

<P>seeking an approach that reinforces partnership,<BR>

<P>voluntary compliance, and common measures of<BR>

<P>performance. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>*Working Principles*:   Agencies should:<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- use market, not administrative, mechanisms<BR>

<P>   wherever possible;<BR>

<P>-- change measures of success to focus on results,<BR>

<P>   not process;<BR>

<P>-- form partnerships with regulated entities and<BR>

<P>   accept informed compliance as their mission;<BR>

<P>-- reward compliance and develop new ways to<BR>

<P>   encourage violators to comply.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Existing models that encourage front line staffs to<BR>

<P>form partnerships should be used as a basis for<BR>

<P>reinvention, such as the Customs Service operation<BR>

<P>in Miami, the &quot;OSH Maine 200&quot; project, and EPA's<BR>

<P>&quot;33/50&quot; program.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Potential questions to be asked by the review group<BR>

<P>might include:<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- Are there regulatory provisions that are<BR>

<P>   especially troublesome to the regulated<BR>

<P>   community that can be reengineered to reduce<BR>

<P>   their intrusiveness while still achieving<BR>

<P>   the intended goals of the program?<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- How can &quot;command and control&quot; regulatory<BR>

<P>   structures be recast into other approaches<BR>

<P>   to make them less intrusive?<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- How can we create systems that target violators<BR>

<P>   instead of treating all members of the regulated<BR>

<P>   community as violators?<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- What examples already exist in agencies of<BR>

<P>   partnerships formed with those being regulated? <BR>

<P>   Can they be built upon?<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- How can agencies change the way they assess the<BR>

<P>   performance of their front line workers and<BR>

<P>   measure their agencies' success so these measures<BR>

<P>   focus on results? <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- How can information technology be used to improve<BR>

<P>   communication with the regulated community --<BR>

<P>   both in disseminating information and obtaining<BR>

<P>   input?<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- How can information technology be used across<BR>

<P>   regulating agencies so they can speak with one<BR>

<P>   voice to the regulated community?<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>*Approach*: This effort will focus on 10-15 major<BR>

<P>regulatory policy areas.  There will be a series of<BR>

<P>seminars for the Vice President around each of these<BR>

<P>policy areas. Some will focus on cross-cutting<BR>

<P>initiatives.  Others will be specific to a<BR>

<P>particular area, such as the environment.  OMB's<BR>

<P>Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs and the<BR>

<P>Office of the Vice President are organizing these<BR>

<P>meetings -- which are being run by each of the major<BR>

<P>White House policy councils and agency staffs with<BR>

<P>jurisdiction over specific policy areas. Following<BR>

<P>these meetings, teams will be formed to put together<BR>

<P>specific proposals.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Participation by regulatory agencies varies,<BR>

<P>depending on the issue involved.  Most regulatory<BR>

<P>agencies are involved via the Regulatory Working<BR>

<P>Group established by E.O. 12866. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>** 4.  Implement Phase I of NPR **<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>*Objective*:  In the summer of 1996, President<BR>

<P>Clinton should be able to tell the American people<BR>

<P>that he has created a results-oriented,<BR>

<P>customer-driven government that is smaller and works<BR>

<P>better -- and that they know it is working better<BR>

<P>from their own personal experience.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>*Principles*:  Create a government that works better<BR>

<P>and costs less by:<BR>

<P>     <BR>

<P>     -- putting customers first<BR>

<P>     -- cutting red tape<BR>

<P>     -- empowering employees<BR>

<P>     -- cutting back to basics<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>*Approach*:  Following are several priority items<BR>

<P>that will be critical to keep on the front burner<BR>

<P>over the next few months while NPR Phase II is in<BR>

<P>high gear:<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>~ Ensure remaining agencies prepare their promised<BR>

<P>  Customer Service Standards, measure performance<BR>

<P>  against these standards, and publish results.<BR>

<P>~ Create a &quot;Virtual Department of Business&quot; to<BR>

<P>  provide a single &quot;face&quot; to businesses that come<BR>

<P>  into contact with the 55 agencies that have set<BR>

<P>   customer service standards for business.<BR>

<P>~ Ensure swift consideration of legislation to<BR>

<P>  reform the civil service.<BR>

<P>~ Continue communication and culture change in the<BR>

<P>  federal government through the use of NetResults<BR>

<P>  -- the NPR information exchange on the Internet --<BR>

<P>  and the NPR newsletter.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>In addition to these key initiatives, we will<BR>

<P>continue tracking the implementation of over 1,200<BR>

<P>other recommendations and, where possible, leverage<BR>

<P>action by others to act on implementation.  We will<BR>

<P>also expand efforts to communicate with federal<BR>

<P>employees via a variety of different initiatives as<BR>

<P>part of our effort to change governmental cultures.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>** 5.  Crosscutting Team **<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>A pool of NPR staff, OMB staff and agency advisors<BR>

<P>will support the three major efforts in Phase II<BR>

<P>(agency restructuring, devolution, regulatory<BR>

<P>reinvention) by operating regular informational<BR>

<P>seminars and providing advice to individual agencies<BR>

<P>and advisory teams.  These staff will have skills<BR>

<P>in:<BR>

<P>     -- privatization and franchising<BR>

<P>     -- streamlining agency and field operations<BR>

<P>     -- identifying opportunities for individual<BR>

<P>        empowerment (e.g., use of vouchers)<BR>

<P>     -- building accountability for results into<BR>

<P>        programs <BR>

<P>     -- developing customer service standards and<BR>

<P>        surveys<BR>

<P>     -- identifying subsidies and other savings.  <BR>

<P>     <BR>

<P>These individuals will work with other NPR staff,<BR>

<P>the agencies, OMB, and White House staff to identify<BR>

<P>options that should be considered.  These people<BR>

<P>would provide options, ideas, and technical support<BR>

<P>to agency and advisory teams.  They will share<BR>

<P>similar innovations across agency lines as well as <BR>

<P>search for new ideas.  They would also be familiar<BR>

<P>with related efforts in states, localities, and<BR>

<P>other countries.   They would, for example, look at<BR>

<P>the OMB&quot; high risk areas&quot; for potential reinvention<BR>

<P>opportunities and talk to groups such as the General<BR>

<P>Accounting Office, the Concord Coalition, Citizens<BR>

<P>Against Waste in Government, and other groups.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>** 6.  Legislative-Executive Branch Relations **<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Using the traditional OMB clearance process, we will<BR>

<P>continue to ensure development of legislation<BR>

<P>designed to implement recommendations made during<BR>

<P>the first phase of NPR that require legislative<BR>

<P>action.  To help assure progress, we will also seek<BR>

<P>to develop an informal working group at the staff<BR>

<P>level with appropriate congressional offices to<BR>

<P>sequence approaches and priorities.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>* What Is the Timetable? *<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- The Vice President sent out a memo on January<BR>

<P>   3rd to agency heads outlining the general<BR>

<P>   principles of the second phase of NPR and invited<BR>

<P>   senior agency representatives to a kickoff<BR>

<P>   meeting January 12th.  Most of the Phase II<BR>

<P>   Steering Group meeting and decisions should be<BR>

<P>   completed before the end of March 1995. <BR>

<P>   Legislative packages for Phase II proposals will<BR>

<P>   be developed and submitted to Congress by early<BR>

<P>   Summer.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- OMB/NPR already provided some background<BR>

<P>   materials to the President's Management<BR>

<P>   Council at its meetings on December 21st and<BR>

<P>   January 4th and the Vice President spoke<BR>

<P>   with the Cabinet about it on January 11th. <BR>

<P>   Additional materials were shared with agencies on<BR>

<P>   January 12th.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- A draft timetable for the delivery of option<BR>

<P>   papers and meetings with the Phase II Steering<BR>

<P>   Group and the Vice President is attached.  This<BR>

<P>   timetable will be continually updated as we go<BR>

<P>   forward.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- While some of NPR Phase II's results are in the<BR>

<P>   FY 1996 budget, most of the work will be done<BR>

<P>   over the next 3 months.  After Presidential<BR>

<P>   decisions are made, agencies will be responsible<BR>

<P>   for drafting implementation legislation. <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>==================================================<BR>

<P>
<P>ATTACHMENTS<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>1. Vice Presidential Memorandum to Agency Heads and<BR>

<P>   Sample Decision Tree for Analyzing Agency<BR>

<P>   Programs<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>2. Sample Outline of Options Paper to be Prepared by<BR>

<P>   Agencies for Meetings with the NPR Phase II<BR>

<P>   Steering Committee and the Vice President<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>3. Procedures for Phase II Steering Committee<BR>

<P>   Meetings<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>=================================================<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>************<BR>

<P>Attachment 2<BR>

<P>************<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>****************************************************<BR>

<P>Outline of Options Paper to be Prepared by Agencies<BR>

<P>for Meetings With the NPR Phase II Steering<BR>

<P>Committee and the Vice President<BR>

<P>****************************************************<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>   <BR>

<P>The Options Paper should be no more than 3-5 pages<BR>

<P>in length, but may include a series of attachments. <BR>

<P>If it seems to more appropriate to prepare separate<BR>

<P>option papers for each of the major components<BR>

<P>within the agency, consult with the lead contact<BR>

<P>point from the NPR Advisory Team to determine if<BR>

<P>this alternative approach would be acceptable.  The<BR>

<P>paper should base its analysis on the Decision Tree<BR>

<P>and answer the questions it raises.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>* Overview * <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Size of agency, when created, number of operating<BR>

<P>units and programs, size of budget. Name key<BR>

<P>functions.  Include any major regulatory or subsidy<BR>

<P>programs that may not necessarily be &quot;on budget.&quot;<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>* Mission and Goals *<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Key programmatic mission and long-term goals to be<BR>

<P>achieved; phrase goals in terms of intended outcomes<BR>

<P>(e.g., reduce infant mortality by 30 percent by<BR>

<P>2005)<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>* Assessment of Key Functions *<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Answer the following questions for each of the key<BR>

<P>functions:<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>-- is this critical to the agency's mission, based<BR>

<P>   on &quot;customer&quot; input?<BR>

<P>-- if no, can it be privatized or terminated?<BR>

<P>-- if yes, can it be done as well or better at the<BR>

<P>   state or local level?<BR>

<P>-- if yes, devolve to states, localities, or<BR>

<P>   individuals.<BR>

<P>-- if no, is there any way to cut costs or improve<BR>

<P>   performance by introducing competition?<BR>

<P>   (competition options include franchising,<BR>

<P>   privatizing, or major reinvention of operations<BR>

<P>   by reengineering)<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>For every major program (or for a crosscutting<BR>

<P>proposal or the entire agency), please respond to<BR>

<P>each of the following two options.  <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>* OPTION 1 -- Terminations of Major Programs (or the<BR>

<P>  entire agency) *<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- Pros, compared with the status quo<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>-- Cons, compared with the status quo<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>----------------------------------------------------<BR>

<P>Summary Cost Information<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>[This was a table in the original document.  For<BR>

<P>each of the numbered fields below (discretionary<BR>

<P>budget authority, etc.), provide the number for each<BR>

<P>year.] <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>----------------------------------------------------<BR>

<P>FY 1996 |Estimated |Estimated |Estimated |5 Yr Cum<BR>

<P>program |resulting |resulting |resulting |FY'96-2000<BR>

<P>levelsin|levels for|levels for|levels for| <BR>

<P>Budget  |FY 1996   |FY 1997   |FY 2000   | <BR>

<P>----------------------------------------------------<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>1. Discretionary Budget Authority<BR>

<P>2. Discretionary Budget Outlays<BR>

<P>3. Mandatory Outlays<BR>

<P>4. Governmental Receipts<BR>

<P>5. FTE Changes<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Note:  all cells do not have to be completed; if it<BR>

<P>is easier to give total dollar changes than total<BR>

<P>dollar amounts, then that is acceptable.  All BA and<BR>

<P>outlay numbers should be net of fees and receipts.<BR>

<P>----------------------------------------------------<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>OPTION 2 -- Restructuring of Major Programs (or<BR>

<P>            entire agency)<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>--   Pros, compared with the status quo<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>--   Cons, compared with the status quo<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>----------------------------------------------------<BR>

<P>Summary Cost Information<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>[This was a table in the original document.  For<BR>

<P>each of the numbered fields below (discretionary<BR>

<P>budget authority, etc.), provide the number for each<BR>

<P>year.] <BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>----------------------------------------------------<BR>

<P>FY 1996 |Estimated |Estimated |Estimated |5 Yr Cum<BR>

<P>program |resulting |resulting |resulting |FY'96-2000<BR>

<P>levelsin|levels for|levels for|levels for| <BR>

<P>Budget  |FY 1996   |FY 1997   |FY 2000   | <BR>

<P>----------------------------------------------------<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>1. Discretionary Budget Authority<BR>

<P>2. Discretionary Budget Outlays<BR>

<P>3. Mandatory Outlays<BR>

<P>4. Governmental Receipts<BR>

<P>5. FTE Changes<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Note:  all cells do not have to be completed; if it<BR>

<P>is easier to give total dollar changes than total<BR>

<P>dollar amounts, then that is acceptable.  All BA and<BR>

<P>outlay numbers should be net of fees and receipts.<BR>

<P>----------------------------------------------------<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>ATTACHMENTS<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>1. Describe any recommendations offered by the<BR>

<P>   OMB/NPR advisory teams that may have been<BR>

<P>   considered but rejected.  Briefly explain why<BR>

<P>   they were rejected.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>2. List programs, functions, subsidies, or<BR>

<P>   regulatory efforts that are not being considered<BR>

<P>   for Phase II reinvention.  Briefly explain why<BR>

<P>   they are being excluded.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>====================================================<BR>

<P>
<P>************<BR>

<P>ATTACHMENT 3<BR>

<P>************<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>Procedures for Phase II Steering Committee Meetings<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>
<P>*Attendance*   Agencies are limited to 6 to 8<BR>

<P>               attendees.  There will be 6-8<BR>

<P>               attendees from OMB, 6-8 from NPR, and<BR>

<P>               2-4 from White House councils or<BR>

<P>               offices.  Total:  20-28.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>*Preparation*  Agencies should deliver 30 copies of<BR>

<P>               their option papers to the primary<BR>

<P>               point of contact on their advisory<BR>

<P>               teams 48 hours in advance of the<BR>

<P>               steering committee presentation.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>               At that time, agencies also shall<BR>

<P>               provide names and titles of<BR>

<P>               attendees. Advisory teams will work<BR>

<P>               with their agencies on the specifics<BR>

<P>               of the presentation agenda.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>*Follow-up*    Advisory teams will meet with agency<BR>

<P>               teams the next workday after the<BR>

<P>               Steering Committee meeting to discuss<BR>

<P>               decisions and next steps.<BR>

<P>
<P>
<P>*Questions*    Scheduling and other questions should<BR>

<P>               be directed to the agency's advisory<BR>

<P>               team primary point of contact.<BR>

<P>
